1
00:01:49,789 --> 00:01:51,425
Here's your coffee, Bernie.

2
00:01:55,628 --> 00:01:57,139
Coffee, Mr. Cook?

3
00:02:03,928 --> 00:02:06,638
If we're going to discuss this,
let's discuss it,

4
00:02:06,639 --> 00:02:09,902
but don't sit there and pout
as if I'd just taken away your tricycle.

5
00:02:10,017 --> 00:02:12,394
I'm not pouting.
I just happen to disagree with you.

6
00:02:12,395 --> 00:02:13,781
But Frank Elgin...

7
00:02:14,188 --> 00:02:16,314
Why not let the doorman read
for the part?

8
00:02:16,315 --> 00:02:17,857
Phil, look at some facts.

9
00:02:17,858 --> 00:02:19,787
We've been in rehearsal for five days.

10
00:02:20,027 --> 00:02:22,153
Our leading man, to put it mildly,
was dreadful.

11
00:02:22,154 --> 00:02:25,073
Now, maybe that was my fault.
Maybe I was the wrong director for him.

12
00:02:25,074 --> 00:02:27,158
At any rate, we let him go yesterday.

13
00:02:27,159 --> 00:02:29,786
As of this morning,
we do not have a replacement.

14
00:02:29,787 --> 00:02:33,748
We open in Boston on the 28th.
We are in trouble.

15
00:02:33,749 --> 00:02:36,293
And I can do without the sarcasm, too.

16
00:02:36,294 --> 00:02:39,838
Cookie, look, all I'm saying is
let me audition him for you.

17
00:02:39,839 --> 00:02:44,009
Phil, after all, there's no harm done
in giving the man a reading.

18
00:02:44,010 --> 00:02:45,938
No. I agree with you.

19
00:02:46,345 --> 00:02:50,515
But when I wanted to read Ray Watson,
that was just a big waste of time.

20
00:02:50,516 --> 00:02:51,891
And he's a much better actor than Elgin.

21
00:02:51,892 --> 00:02:54,269
I know a lot of guys
who can act better than Elgin.

22
00:02:54,270 --> 00:02:56,354
And I know a lot of guys
who can sing better.

23
00:02:56,355 --> 00:02:58,607
But I can't think of anybody
who can do both as well.

24
00:02:58,608 --> 00:03:01,651
- What about Billy Hertz?
- He's stiff, pompous.

25
00:03:01,652 --> 00:03:04,404
Look, Cookie, this isn't
<i>Student Prince</i> or <i>Blossom Time.</i>

26
00:03:04,405 --> 00:03:06,781
The guy who plays this part
has to act while he's singing

27
00:03:06,782 --> 00:03:08,586
and sing while he's acting.

28
00:03:08,743 --> 00:03:10,535
You never saw <i>Lonesome Town.</i>

29
00:03:10,536 --> 00:03:13,955
Elgin played a part exactly like this,
and he was just magnificent in it.

30
00:03:13,956 --> 00:03:16,207
All right, don't take my word for it.
Ask Henry.

31
00:03:16,208 --> 00:03:17,709
He played the piano in the pit
for that show.

32
00:03:17,710 --> 00:03:19,972
- When was that?
- Seven or eight years ago.

33
00:03:20,087 --> 00:03:22,213
He wasn't falling off bar stools then.

34
00:03:22,214 --> 00:03:24,007
I hear he hasn't had a drink
in a long time.

35
00:03:24,008 --> 00:03:27,427
- To a drunk, 10 minutes is a long time.
- I'm not asking you to live with him!

36
00:03:27,428 --> 00:03:29,012
I just want you to listen to him!

37
00:03:29,013 --> 00:03:30,805
All right! Go ahead! Go ahead!

38
00:03:30,806 --> 00:03:32,151
- Go ahead!
- Larry!

39
00:03:33,267 --> 00:03:34,467
Larry?

40
00:03:35,019 --> 00:03:37,395
- As soon as Elgin comes in, I want...
- He's here waiting.

41
00:03:37,396 --> 00:03:39,022
I didn't want to interrupt you
while you were...

42
00:03:39,023 --> 00:03:40,223
Send him in.

43
00:03:41,317 --> 00:03:43,913
Now, Cookie, no cracks, please.

44
00:03:58,709 --> 00:04:00,877
What are you fellows
auditioning out there, owls?

45
00:04:00,878 --> 00:04:02,181
Hello, Frank.

46
00:04:03,297 --> 00:04:04,714
- Bernie Dodd.
- How do you do?

47
00:04:04,715 --> 00:04:07,102
- This is our producer, Mr. Cook.
- How do you do, Mr. Cook?

48
00:04:07,802 --> 00:04:09,271
Hello. How are you?

49
00:04:09,387 --> 00:04:11,774
Paul Ungen
and you know Henry Johnson.

50
00:04:11,889 --> 00:04:14,474
- Hey, Henry.
- Hello, Frank. It's been a long time.

51
00:04:14,475 --> 00:04:16,935
Gee, I told this guy years ago
to stop playing other people's music

52
00:04:16,936 --> 00:04:18,395
and write some of his own.

53
00:04:18,396 --> 00:04:19,646
So, you took my advice?

54
00:04:19,647 --> 00:04:21,106
- How's the family?
- Fine.

55
00:04:21,107 --> 00:04:23,441
Guess that big boy of yours
is in high school by now.

56
00:04:23,442 --> 00:04:25,151
- He's in the Air Force.
- No.

57
00:04:25,152 --> 00:04:26,903
Yes, he is.

58
00:04:26,904 --> 00:04:29,208
Now let's get started.
I've got a luncheon date.

59
00:04:31,200 --> 00:04:33,702
Frank, this is an offbeat kind of show.

60
00:04:33,703 --> 00:04:36,204
It's a dramatization
of The Land <i>Around Us.</i>

61
00:04:36,205 --> 00:04:38,592
- You remember the book?
- Yeah, sure.

62
00:04:38,833 --> 00:04:40,583
Well, the boys have done what I consider

63
00:04:40,584 --> 00:04:43,002
a kind of an exciting musical adaptation.

64
00:04:43,003 --> 00:04:44,921
No numbers exactly.

65
00:04:44,922 --> 00:04:47,340
The music is part of the fabric,
woven in and out.

66
00:04:47,341 --> 00:04:49,342
That's the way to keep the seats
from getting dusty.

67
00:04:49,343 --> 00:04:50,896
Give 'em something different.

68
00:04:51,178 --> 00:04:52,378
Yeah.

69
00:04:52,638 --> 00:04:55,734
Would you mind reading
a couple of scenes for Mr. Cook?

70
00:04:55,933 --> 00:04:58,893
- There's one in the first act.
- Excuse me, Bernie, for interrupting,

71
00:04:58,894 --> 00:05:02,105
but you were speaking
<i>of</i> Lonesome Town a minute ago.

72
00:05:02,106 --> 00:05:04,535
Maybe Frank could do
the pitchman number.

73
00:05:04,692 --> 00:05:06,912
That'd show Phil
everything you want him to see.

74
00:05:07,111 --> 00:05:10,165
- It's all right with me if...
- I don't know if I remember it.

75
00:05:10,322 --> 00:05:13,085
- You sure you do?
- I certainly should.

76
00:05:13,367 --> 00:05:16,213
Eight performances a week
for a year and a half.

77
00:05:16,328 --> 00:05:18,455
Maybe you ought to describe
the number to Mr. Cook.

78
00:05:18,456 --> 00:05:20,467
- Give him a kind of a lead-in.
- Okay.

79
00:05:21,167 --> 00:05:23,084
Well, it wasn't much, really.

80
00:05:23,085 --> 00:05:25,681
It was just a thing where I played
one of those pitchmen.

81
00:05:26,088 --> 00:05:27,881
Sort of a fanciful character,

82
00:05:27,882 --> 00:05:30,967
only instead of selling a patent
medicine or something like that,

83
00:05:30,968 --> 00:05:32,677
I was selling a philosophy.

84
00:05:32,678 --> 00:05:35,221
You know, sort of a sunshine salesman.

85
00:05:35,222 --> 00:05:37,318
And the scene was
a New York street corner,

86
00:05:37,600 --> 00:05:41,447
and I worked under
a lamppost like this, and I had a...

87
00:05:42,146 --> 00:05:43,772
Is it okay if I use this for a minute?

88
00:05:43,773 --> 00:05:45,993
- Use anything you like.
- Thanks.

89
00:05:49,612 --> 00:05:51,738
And now, when I made my entrance,
I was carrying...

90
00:05:51,739 --> 00:05:54,157
Okay, okay, I get it.

91
00:05:54,158 --> 00:05:55,628
Now, let's get on with it.

92
00:05:56,160 --> 00:05:57,360
Right.

93
00:05:57,578 --> 00:06:00,747
I just wanted to say
I was carrying an imaginary valise,

94
00:06:00,748 --> 00:06:03,374
you know,
one of those pitchmen's outfits?

95
00:06:03,375 --> 00:06:04,720
Okay, Henry.

96
00:06:22,061 --> 00:06:25,282
And then a crowd of sourpusses
begin to gather around, you see?

97
00:06:25,981 --> 00:06:28,775
<i>Hurry, hurry, hurry, hurry, hurry</i>

98
00:06:28,776 --> 00:06:31,361
<i>And... That's a little high for me, Henry</i>

99
00:06:31,362 --> 00:06:33,696
<i>Can you get it down a tone?</i>

100
00:06:33,697 --> 00:06:36,658
<i>Hurry, hurry, hurry, hurry, hurry</i>

101
00:06:36,659 --> 00:06:40,422
<i>And do away with
worry, worry, worry, worry</i>

102
00:06:41,580 --> 00:06:44,666
<i>Sometime or other, brother</i>

103
00:06:44,667 --> 00:06:48,222
<i>Everybody gets his back to the wall</i>

104
00:06:48,546 --> 00:06:52,173
<i>History discloses life's no bed of roses
And that's for darn sure</i>

105
00:06:52,174 --> 00:06:55,646
<i>Kings topple and nations fall</i>

106
00:06:56,136 --> 00:06:57,887
<i>Rich man, poor man, Indian chief</i>

107
00:06:57,888 --> 00:06:59,973
<i>How, Chief!
He's a left-handed Indian, this kid</i>

108
00:06:59,974 --> 00:07:02,528
<i>I include you all</i>

109
00:07:02,935 --> 00:07:05,144
<i>Simpletons, noodle-heads</i>

110
00:07:05,145 --> 00:07:07,188
<i>You're off</i>

111
00:07:07,189 --> 00:07:10,995
<i>If you don't take advantage of my cure-all</i>

112
00:07:12,486 --> 00:07:14,362
Now, friends,
I tell you what I'm going to do.

113
00:07:14,363 --> 00:07:17,073
I have here in this little valise here
nostrums, cure-alls, panaceas,

114
00:07:17,074 --> 00:07:20,702
unguents, oils, and the healing waters.

115
00:07:20,703 --> 00:07:22,579
What did you say, son?

116
00:07:22,580 --> 00:07:24,174
You say the valise is empty?

117
00:07:25,040 --> 00:07:26,916
Son, this valise is loaded.

118
00:07:26,917 --> 00:07:29,805
You're just looking at it with your eyes,
and your windows are foggy.

119
00:07:31,297 --> 00:07:34,601
What did you say, friend?
You say you can't see nothing, either?

120
00:07:35,009 --> 00:07:36,509
Well, friend, let me tell you something.

121
00:07:36,510 --> 00:07:38,803
There's no trick in believing
in just what you see.

122
00:07:38,804 --> 00:07:41,764
The trick is in
believing in what you can't see.

123
00:07:41,765 --> 00:07:44,862
You've got to visualize the indiscernible.
For instance...

124
00:07:45,686 --> 00:07:49,522
<i>Here's a moonbeam
that wants to go peeping in</i>

125
00:07:49,523 --> 00:07:51,952
<i>Here's the lilt that the bluebird shares</i>

126
00:07:53,736 --> 00:07:57,207
<i>Here's a tropical night to go sleeping in</i>

127
00:07:57,740 --> 00:08:02,546
<i>Step up and sample my wares</i>

128
00:08:02,745 --> 00:08:04,996
Every item in this valise,
ladies and gentlemen,

129
00:08:04,997 --> 00:08:08,177
belongs to you as well
as it does to me.

130
00:08:08,667 --> 00:08:12,086
<i>Here's the silver moon
from the sky up there</i>

131
00:08:12,087 --> 00:08:15,392
<i>And the emerald meadow outdoors
Oh, yes</i>

132
00:08:15,716 --> 00:08:19,093
<i>For the wealth of treasure
there is to share</i>

133
00:08:19,094 --> 00:08:20,731
<i>It's mine</i>

134
00:08:20,846 --> 00:08:22,472
<i>It's yours</i>

135
00:08:22,473 --> 00:08:25,934
<i>Now, if you live a dream
oh, how precious is</i>

136
00:08:25,935 --> 00:08:29,187
<i>An imagination that soars</i>

137
00:08:29,188 --> 00:08:34,484
<i>It can make this world we're in
Hers and his and mine</i>

138
00:08:34,485 --> 00:08:36,194
<i>And yours</i>

139
00:08:36,195 --> 00:08:39,572
<i>Now, if you want blue skies about</i>

140
00:08:39,573 --> 00:08:41,115
<i>Year in</i>

141
00:08:41,116 --> 00:08:42,753
<i>Year out</i>

142
00:08:43,285 --> 00:08:48,467
<i>All you ever need in the last analysis</i>

143
00:08:48,749 --> 00:08:50,333
<i>Is this</i>

144
00:08:50,334 --> 00:08:53,628
<i>Try a cheerful song and a valentine</i>

145
00:08:53,629 --> 00:08:56,725
<i>And a sense of humor that scores</i>

146
00:08:57,257 --> 00:08:58,967
<i>You're no longer in a spin</i>

147
00:08:58,968 --> 00:09:00,885
<i>It's a great world we're in</i>

148
00:09:00,886 --> 00:09:02,773
<i>And it's mine</i>

149
00:09:03,889 --> 00:09:05,692
<i>It's yours</i>

150
00:09:07,267 --> 00:09:08,737
What's that you say, Officer?

151
00:09:10,020 --> 00:09:11,532
Have I got a license?

152
00:09:11,689 --> 00:09:15,024
Just got the greatest license
in the world, poetic license.

153
00:09:15,025 --> 00:09:16,234
What did you say?

154
00:09:16,235 --> 00:09:18,831
You've been listening to my pitch?

155
00:09:19,029 --> 00:09:20,874
We're going to the station house?

156
00:09:22,908 --> 00:09:24,784
You got a desk sergeant down there

157
00:09:24,785 --> 00:09:26,452
who's a little on the prod,
a little on the muscle,

158
00:09:26,453 --> 00:09:28,162
a little on the cantankerous side?

159
00:09:28,163 --> 00:09:29,466
Here's how we'll handle his case.

160
00:09:29,748 --> 00:09:33,543
<i>With a cheerful song and a valentine</i>

161
00:09:33,544 --> 00:09:36,390
<i>And a sense of humor that scores</i>

162
00:09:36,672 --> 00:09:40,425
<i>You're no longer in a spin
It's a great world you're in</i>

163
00:09:40,426 --> 00:09:42,062
<i>And it's mine</i>

164
00:09:43,512 --> 00:09:44,940
<i>It's yours</i>

165
00:09:46,807 --> 00:09:48,443
<i>And it's hers</i>

166
00:09:50,310 --> 00:09:51,686
<i>And it's his</i>

167
00:09:51,687 --> 00:09:53,146
Share it among your friends.

168
00:09:53,147 --> 00:09:56,189
If you got some of it on you,
tell 'em where you got it.

169
00:09:58,819 --> 00:10:01,904
Thanks, Henry. You always did have
a good beat for a writer, you know that?

170
00:10:01,905 --> 00:10:03,114
Fine, Frank, fine.

171
00:10:03,115 --> 00:10:04,323
You ought to hear it with an orchestra.

172
00:10:04,324 --> 00:10:06,545
It's much... It's good and lousy.

173
00:10:07,161 --> 00:10:08,922
Would you wait outside for a second?

174
00:10:09,246 --> 00:10:11,873
Say, I'm a little in the dark about this.

175
00:10:11,874 --> 00:10:14,052
What's it for, a musical spot?

176
00:10:14,251 --> 00:10:15,418
A small part or what?

177
00:10:15,419 --> 00:10:16,722
It's the lead, Frank.

178
00:10:17,421 --> 00:10:19,474
The whole show is built
around this character.

179
00:10:30,309 --> 00:10:31,726
Well, what do you think?

180
00:10:31,727 --> 00:10:33,614
Didn't it speak for itself?

181
00:10:33,979 --> 00:10:35,855
Bernie, he's probably
been doing that material

182
00:10:35,856 --> 00:10:38,316
at dinner parties for the last 10 years.

183
00:10:38,317 --> 00:10:41,360
Did it prove he's worth risking
over $200,000 on?

184
00:10:41,361 --> 00:10:43,738
Did it prove he can carry a whole show?

185
00:10:43,739 --> 00:10:45,573
Bernie, be sensible.

186
00:10:45,574 --> 00:10:48,086
That guy has been laying in the pickle,
ever since you were a kid.

187
00:10:48,952 --> 00:10:51,913
Someone once took a chance
with an actress named Laurette Taylor

188
00:10:51,914 --> 00:10:54,123
in <i>The Glass Menagerie,</i>
and look what she did.

189
00:10:54,124 --> 00:10:56,845
Bernie, tell me something.
What are you trying to prove?

190
00:10:57,252 --> 00:10:59,128
You've got a good book, good music.

191
00:10:59,129 --> 00:11:01,964
Why can't you be satisfied
with a good, reliable,

192
00:11:01,965 --> 00:11:03,591
adequate, normal, sober actor?

193
00:11:03,592 --> 00:11:07,804
Because he'll give you a good, reliable,
adequate, normal, sober performance.

194
00:11:07,805 --> 00:11:10,275
And that's not what people
pay $6.60 to see.

195
00:11:10,432 --> 00:11:12,809
On the last show, you fought me
every step of the way with Danelli.

196
00:11:12,810 --> 00:11:14,602
And I still think you were wrong.

197
00:11:14,603 --> 00:11:17,074
Instead of taking an actor
and teaching him how to box,

198
00:11:17,189 --> 00:11:18,856
you have to go to Stillman's Gym

199
00:11:18,857 --> 00:11:20,775
and get a punch-drunk fighter
and teach him how to act.

200
00:11:20,776 --> 00:11:22,235
He gave you a great performance,
didn't he?

201
00:11:22,236 --> 00:11:24,445
Yes. He gave us a lot of trouble, too.

202
00:11:24,446 --> 00:11:27,115
He was cracked.
If there was a good fight at the Garden,

203
00:11:27,116 --> 00:11:28,908
he just wouldn't show up
for the performance.

204
00:11:28,909 --> 00:11:30,295
Cookie, I promise you,

205
00:11:30,536 --> 00:11:33,788
with Elgin, you're apt to get something
that happens once in 20 years.

206
00:11:33,789 --> 00:11:36,457
I know it'll be a lot of hard work,
but I'll get it out of him.

207
00:11:36,458 --> 00:11:38,595
You're good, Bernie,
but you're not that good.

208
00:11:39,419 --> 00:11:41,838
That's what people have been saying
to me since I was this high.

209
00:11:41,839 --> 00:11:44,132
So, now you're going to show them.

210
00:11:44,133 --> 00:11:45,435
Every one of them.

211
00:11:45,926 --> 00:11:47,927
Just directing
doesn't satisfy you any longer.

212
00:11:47,928 --> 00:11:50,482
Now, you want to take a corpse
and breathe life into it.

213
00:11:51,640 --> 00:11:53,443
Maybe I'm crazy, but...

214
00:11:54,059 --> 00:11:55,810
Doesn't this worry you guys?

215
00:11:55,811 --> 00:11:57,531
Not if it doesn't worry Bernie.

216
00:11:59,565 --> 00:12:01,274
He's too old for the part.

217
00:12:01,275 --> 00:12:04,443
We'll get a couple of hairpieces.
We'll make him look 10 years younger.

218
00:12:04,444 --> 00:12:06,581
All right, all right, Bernie.

219
00:12:06,780 --> 00:12:09,448
But could we at least look around for
someone else while he's rehearsing?

220
00:12:09,449 --> 00:12:12,368
No. No, once we start with him,
we don't let him go without real cause.

221
00:12:12,369 --> 00:12:15,590
A binge is a real cause,
or if he can't retain lines.

222
00:12:15,789 --> 00:12:18,291
And I want to give him a run-of-the-play
contract, no two-week deal.

223
00:12:18,292 --> 00:12:19,333
Now wait a minute...

224
00:12:19,334 --> 00:12:20,751
Because I need his complete confidence.

225
00:12:20,752 --> 00:12:23,296
We give him a two-weeks clause,
he knows we can let him go at any time.

226
00:12:23,297 --> 00:12:26,507
No, sir.
I'm in for a $40,000 bite already.

227
00:12:26,508 --> 00:12:29,135
But I'll take that loss before
I'll give him a run-of-the-play contract!

228
00:12:29,136 --> 00:12:30,981
Okay, Phil, two weeks.
Agreed with you, Paul?

229
00:12:31,388 --> 00:12:33,233
- Henry?
- Okay with me.

230
00:12:33,849 --> 00:12:35,235
Frank?

231
00:12:35,851 --> 00:12:37,476
Frank Elgin!

232
00:12:37,477 --> 00:12:38,677
Elgin?

233
00:12:38,979 --> 00:12:40,313
He's gone. He left.

234
00:12:40,314 --> 00:12:42,398
- What do you mean he left?
- He left.

235
00:12:42,399 --> 00:12:43,774
Where? Coffee, what?

236
00:12:43,775 --> 00:12:45,537
He just walked out, Bernie. He didn't say.

237
00:12:50,240 --> 00:12:51,710
Try the nearest bar.

238
00:13:41,541 --> 00:13:43,042
Mr. Elgin in?

239
00:13:43,043 --> 00:13:44,168
No, he's not.

240
00:13:44,169 --> 00:13:45,369
You Mrs. Elgin?

241
00:13:46,046 --> 00:13:48,256
I'd like to talk to Frank.
I'm Bernie Dodd.

242
00:13:48,257 --> 00:13:49,840
How do you do?

243
00:13:49,841 --> 00:13:51,342
I don't know when Frank will be back.

244
00:13:51,343 --> 00:13:53,647
- Mind if I wait?
- Well...

245
00:13:58,725 --> 00:14:00,726
I was just going to have some coffee.
Would you like some?

246
00:14:00,727 --> 00:14:01,894
No, thanks.

247
00:14:01,895 --> 00:14:03,490
Frank say when he'd be back?

248
00:14:03,772 --> 00:14:05,534
He didn't say where he was going.

249
00:14:07,317 --> 00:14:09,944
Didn't he tell you he had
an audition with me this morning?

250
00:14:09,945 --> 00:14:11,145
No.

251
00:14:11,738 --> 00:14:14,084
I looked around after it was over,
but he'd gone.

252
00:14:15,075 --> 00:14:16,545
Will he do?

253
00:14:17,661 --> 00:14:18,964
That all depends.

254
00:14:36,346 --> 00:14:40,026
If you're wondering if you can get Frank
for very little money, you can.

255
00:14:40,726 --> 00:14:42,320
Doesn't depend on that.

256
00:14:42,602 --> 00:14:44,281
Does he still drink?

257
00:14:45,856 --> 00:14:49,483
Now, just what did you think
I would answer to that, Mr. Dodd?

258
00:14:49,484 --> 00:14:50,704
- Touché.
- What?

259
00:14:51,111 --> 00:14:52,862
"Touché." In French that means...

260
00:14:52,863 --> 00:14:55,500
Come on, everybody knows
what "touché" means.

261
00:14:56,325 --> 00:14:58,211
You're even younger than I thought.

262
00:14:59,411 --> 00:15:01,882
And you try to look like an old lady,
and you're not.

263
00:15:02,080 --> 00:15:03,717
Shouldn't wear your hair like that.

264
00:15:04,708 --> 00:15:06,125
There are two kinds of women,

265
00:15:06,126 --> 00:15:08,044
those who pay too much attention
to themselves

266
00:15:08,045 --> 00:15:09,245
and those who don't pay enough.

267
00:15:09,421 --> 00:15:11,672
Say, that's quite a pearl of wisdom.

268
00:15:11,673 --> 00:15:13,393
May I quote you?

269
00:15:15,802 --> 00:15:17,814
How long you and Frank been married?

270
00:15:19,139 --> 00:15:21,057
- Ten years.
- Where'd you meet, in a show?

271
00:15:21,058 --> 00:15:22,850
Now, look, Mr. Dodd, don't you think...

272
00:15:22,851 --> 00:15:24,643
I'm just trying to find out
if you were ever an actress.

273
00:15:24,644 --> 00:15:26,656
No, not me, thank you.

274
00:15:27,481 --> 00:15:29,273
I'm just a girl from the country.

275
00:15:29,274 --> 00:15:33,622
The theater and the people in it have
always been a complete mystery to me.

276
00:15:34,446 --> 00:15:35,646
They still are.

277
00:15:41,578 --> 00:15:44,341
Dreiser, Balzac, Montaigne...

278
00:15:45,248 --> 00:15:47,552
- Who reads these books?
- I do.

279
00:15:49,378 --> 00:15:52,421
I'm afraid to ask you if you enjoy them.
You'd bite my head off.

280
00:15:52,422 --> 00:15:53,683
Montaigne's too polite for me.

281
00:15:54,508 --> 00:15:55,977
That doesn't surprise me.

282
00:15:58,136 --> 00:15:59,336
Frank's old recordings?

283
00:15:59,638 --> 00:16:01,013
Some new.

284
00:16:01,014 --> 00:16:02,859
The one on the machine
he did last week.

285
00:16:27,541 --> 00:16:29,135
A man with his talent.

286
00:16:29,709 --> 00:16:31,012
It's degrading.

287
00:16:31,878 --> 00:16:33,473
So is not eating.

288
00:16:36,049 --> 00:16:37,310
Why didn't you wait?

289
00:16:39,428 --> 00:16:41,220
I figured the boat had sailed.

290
00:16:41,221 --> 00:16:43,525
I had a feeling
the producer didn't like me.

291
00:16:43,765 --> 00:16:45,516
Since when does it have to be
in an actor's contract

292
00:16:45,517 --> 00:16:46,987
the producer has to love him?

293
00:16:47,352 --> 00:16:50,407
Well, I can't go to bat
unless I feel everybody's rooting for me.

294
00:16:51,940 --> 00:16:55,067
- Cook thinks you're a drinker.
- No, I don't booze it up on a show.

295
00:16:55,068 --> 00:16:56,871
Not according to Maxwell. I checked.

296
00:16:57,737 --> 00:16:59,447
You worked for him in '46.

297
00:16:59,448 --> 00:17:01,251
After a couple of months,
he had to replace you.

298
00:17:04,411 --> 00:17:06,464
While I was playing in that show, our...

299
00:17:07,247 --> 00:17:08,456
Our son died.

300
00:17:08,457 --> 00:17:10,594
All right, that takes care of that show.
What about this one?

301
00:17:10,709 --> 00:17:13,054
I need an actor who can stay sober
and learn lines.

302
00:17:13,336 --> 00:17:15,713
- Are you that actor or not?
- I don't...

303
00:17:15,714 --> 00:17:16,964
Make up your mind.

304
00:17:16,965 --> 00:17:18,716
Give me a little time.

305
00:17:18,717 --> 00:17:21,646
Cook wasn't the only reason
I left the theater just now.

306
00:17:21,928 --> 00:17:23,607
I wanted to talk it over with my wife.

307
00:17:24,181 --> 00:17:26,056
Gee, I wouldn't think of taking
a part like this

308
00:17:26,057 --> 00:17:27,850
without talking it over
with Georgie first.

309
00:17:27,851 --> 00:17:29,435
All right, talk it over.
I'll be back in 10 minutes.

310
00:17:29,436 --> 00:17:31,270
Mr. Dodd, don't you see?

311
00:17:31,271 --> 00:17:33,325
He's afraid of the responsibility.

312
00:17:33,440 --> 00:17:36,275
But I'm the one that's taking the chance.
The gamble's all on my side.

313
00:17:36,276 --> 00:17:38,652
It's not a question
of being afraid of the responsibility.

314
00:17:38,653 --> 00:17:40,665
It's just that...

315
00:17:41,156 --> 00:17:43,460
Well, the part's the whole show.
You said so yourself.

316
00:17:44,659 --> 00:17:46,744
Gee, you've been rehearsing five days,

317
00:17:46,745 --> 00:17:48,662
and you're opening in Boston the 28th.

318
00:17:48,663 --> 00:17:51,165
I don't think I could
learn the lines in that time.

319
00:17:51,166 --> 00:17:53,501
You need a Walter Huston
or somebody like that.

320
00:17:53,502 --> 00:17:55,461
It's bad enough to go
to Hollywood to cast.

321
00:17:55,462 --> 00:17:57,223
Now, you suggest I go to heaven.

322
00:17:58,548 --> 00:18:00,716
You can do it, Frank. I know you can.

323
00:18:00,717 --> 00:18:02,520
Why are you so sure?

324
00:18:02,677 --> 00:18:06,096
Because when I first saw him, I was
a hatcheck boy at the Shubert Theatre.

325
00:18:06,097 --> 00:18:08,140
You, Lunt and Jolson,
you were my heroes.

326
00:18:08,141 --> 00:18:09,444
I know everything you've done.

327
00:18:09,601 --> 00:18:12,895
Naturally, Mr. Dodd, you exaggerate
the sentiment to make your point.

328
00:18:12,896 --> 00:18:14,605
Are you for him or against him?

329
00:18:14,606 --> 00:18:15,981
I'm his wife.

330
00:18:15,982 --> 00:18:18,953
All I want is complete honesty
from both of you.

331
00:18:19,110 --> 00:18:22,207
Flattery is cheap, Mr. Dodd.
How about a little costly truth?

332
00:18:24,449 --> 00:18:25,835
All right.

333
00:18:26,868 --> 00:18:28,744
I'm not blind to Frank's condition.

334
00:18:28,745 --> 00:18:30,955
One look at this room tells me
what he is.

335
00:18:30,956 --> 00:18:32,665
And I'm not one of
those nice, friendly people

336
00:18:32,666 --> 00:18:36,137
who slaps you on the back, buys you
a drink and that's as far as it goes.

337
00:18:36,419 --> 00:18:38,587
If you take this job, Frank,
I won't leave you on a limb.

338
00:18:38,588 --> 00:18:41,006
We'll work together and worry together.

339
00:18:41,007 --> 00:18:44,521
But if you do me dirt, just once, no pity.

340
00:18:45,178 --> 00:18:47,054
Not a drop of pity.

341
00:18:47,055 --> 00:18:48,764
No pity, I like that.

342
00:18:48,765 --> 00:18:50,694
Now, at least he knows what to expect.

343
00:18:51,476 --> 00:18:53,060
What kind of a contract do you offer?

344
00:18:53,061 --> 00:18:54,353
- Honey...
- Standard two-week contract.

345
00:18:54,354 --> 00:18:55,688
- Not run-of-the-play?
- No.

346
00:18:55,689 --> 00:18:58,357
Doesn't that mean you could let Frank
out anytime with two weeks' notice?

347
00:18:58,358 --> 00:19:00,943
- That's exactly what it means.
- You just said he needed confidence.

348
00:19:00,944 --> 00:19:04,071
He won't have it with a two-week clause
over his head. Would you?

349
00:19:04,072 --> 00:19:07,491
I have nothing in my mind
except for Frank to play this part.

350
00:19:07,492 --> 00:19:09,201
That sentiment again.

351
00:19:09,202 --> 00:19:11,412
- Dear Lord.
- What is this?

352
00:19:11,413 --> 00:19:13,455
I come up here
with the best intentions in the world,

353
00:19:13,456 --> 00:19:15,124
and suddenly, I find I'm victimizing you.

354
00:19:15,125 --> 00:19:16,292
Can I get a word in?

355
00:19:16,293 --> 00:19:18,043
What'd I bring you, a basket of snakes?

356
00:19:18,044 --> 00:19:20,014
It's not the two-weeks clause.

357
00:19:21,006 --> 00:19:23,966
It's just that I don't want to bite off
more than I can chew, that's all.

358
00:19:23,967 --> 00:19:25,634
You got the offer. Make up your mind.

359
00:19:25,635 --> 00:19:27,564
We're booked into Boston for two weeks.

360
00:19:27,804 --> 00:19:28,971
The season's still young.

361
00:19:28,972 --> 00:19:30,400
We could stay out
until you were letter-perfect.

362
00:19:31,057 --> 00:19:33,361
- Would you do that?
- Do it? I'd insist on it.

363
00:19:34,936 --> 00:19:37,605
Talk it over with your agent here
and call the office by 3:00.

364
00:19:37,606 --> 00:19:39,284
And that means not later.

365
00:19:42,319 --> 00:19:43,872
Need a $20 bill?

366
00:19:51,369 --> 00:19:52,569
You need it.

367
00:19:56,708 --> 00:19:59,679
Why did you have to make
that crack about responsibility for?

368
00:20:05,050 --> 00:20:08,229
Why didn't you tell me
about that audition this morning, Frank?

369
00:20:09,179 --> 00:20:11,524
Because I wasn't sure
whether I could make it or not.

370
00:20:13,975 --> 00:20:16,435
I must've walked up and down
47th Street a dozen times

371
00:20:16,436 --> 00:20:18,114
before I could make myself
go through with it.

372
00:20:18,938 --> 00:20:20,784
Don't keep things from me.

373
00:20:21,650 --> 00:20:24,454
- I can't do it, can I?
- Of course you can.

374
00:20:24,611 --> 00:20:27,446
You've got to try again,
and this seems a perfect opportunity.

375
00:20:27,447 --> 00:20:29,751
Well, if I do take it, Georgie,
I'll need you,

376
00:20:30,075 --> 00:20:32,796
every second, every step of the way.

377
00:20:33,828 --> 00:20:37,467
I don't have any appointments, Frank,
all winter.

378
00:20:37,707 --> 00:20:39,416
I wish it were a run-of-the-play contract.

379
00:20:39,417 --> 00:20:41,835
Well, then why didn't you tell him that
when I brought it up?

380
00:20:41,836 --> 00:20:43,003
Because I didn't want to antagonize him.

381
00:20:43,004 --> 00:20:44,254
After all, if I do take the part,
I'm the one

382
00:20:44,255 --> 00:20:46,382
that's going to have
to work with him, you know, not you.

383
00:20:46,383 --> 00:20:47,716
Well, you'll never get a better deal.

384
00:20:47,717 --> 00:20:49,562
They won't give you perfect terms.

385
00:20:49,928 --> 00:20:51,940
So, take it and do your level best.

386
00:20:54,099 --> 00:20:55,808
Wait a minute. Wait a minute here.

387
00:20:55,809 --> 00:20:57,111
Two-weeks clause.

388
00:20:57,936 --> 00:20:59,614
They can give me notice anytime,

389
00:21:00,355 --> 00:21:02,492
but I can give them notice, too.

390
00:21:03,900 --> 00:21:05,745
I can walk out anytime I want.

391
00:21:06,569 --> 00:21:07,861
If I feel it isn't working out, I...

392
00:21:07,862 --> 00:21:09,624
You mean you can quit, Frank?

393
00:21:09,739 --> 00:21:11,251
No, not the way you mean it.

394
00:21:12,867 --> 00:21:14,451
But if the show doesn't pan out,

395
00:21:14,452 --> 00:21:16,464
I certainly don't want
to come into New York in a turkey.

396
00:21:18,164 --> 00:21:19,884
But maybe this time,
it will work out, though.

397
00:21:20,375 --> 00:21:24,013
Bernie likes me,
and Henry Johnson's pulling for me.

398
00:21:25,255 --> 00:21:26,891
That guy, Cook, I got to worry about.

399
00:21:28,925 --> 00:21:31,896
Ever since we've settled here,
we've been having trouble, Joe.

400
00:21:32,137 --> 00:21:33,762
And now, instead of fields of wheat,

401
00:21:33,763 --> 00:21:36,526
we got nothing but stubble
rotting in the brown dust.

402
00:21:36,975 --> 00:21:38,475
I've talked it over with Stella.

403
00:21:38,476 --> 00:21:40,113
We've had enough. We're leaving.

404
00:21:41,479 --> 00:21:43,355
Well, what are we waiting for?
Let's push on.

405
00:21:43,356 --> 00:21:45,023
There's nothing to stay around here for.

406
00:21:45,024 --> 00:21:47,120
- How about you, Joe?
- I'm staying.

407
00:21:47,944 --> 00:21:50,946
You know, they say sometimes
when a man falls from a great height,

408
00:21:50,947 --> 00:21:53,877
before he hits bottom,
his whole life flashes by.

409
00:21:54,200 --> 00:21:58,089
In one split second, he sees himself
for what he was and what he is.

410
00:21:58,872 --> 00:22:01,290
But you don't always
have to plummet like a hailstone

411
00:22:01,291 --> 00:22:02,916
to face that split second.

412
00:22:02,917 --> 00:22:04,117
Mean it, Frank, mean it!

413
00:22:05,879 --> 00:22:08,433
To plummet like a hailstone
to face that split second.

414
00:22:08,882 --> 00:22:11,144
It can come to you as it did to me today,

415
00:22:11,259 --> 00:22:12,459
as you stand...

416
00:22:13,344 --> 00:22:14,564
It can, if...

417
00:22:15,180 --> 00:22:16,524
What is it, Larry?

418
00:22:16,639 --> 00:22:18,307
"In the middle of a smoldering field."

419
00:22:18,308 --> 00:22:20,517
As you stand in the middle
of a smoldering field,

420
00:22:20,518 --> 00:22:24,104
and you see your prayers and hopes
go up in wisps of smoke.

421
00:22:24,105 --> 00:22:25,856
It's nothing, Frank, just nothing.

422
00:22:25,857 --> 00:22:28,661
This is the most important decision
in the man's life.

423
00:22:28,777 --> 00:22:29,943
The way you're playing him,

424
00:22:29,944 --> 00:22:32,874
it sounds like he's trying to decide
what kind of eggs to have for breakfast.

425
00:22:33,740 --> 00:22:35,293
And that goes for the rest of you, too.

426
00:22:35,617 --> 00:22:39,411
I'm sorry, Bernie, it's just that
I'm still fighting these words.

427
00:22:39,412 --> 00:22:42,342
You should've had 'em licked by now.
We've been in rehearsal 10 days.

428
00:22:42,457 --> 00:22:45,011
- All right, let's take it from...
- Bernie.

429
00:22:45,627 --> 00:22:47,013
It can't be that late.

430
00:22:48,379 --> 00:22:49,933
Where does it go?

431
00:22:50,507 --> 00:22:52,424
All right, knock off. Same time tomorrow.

432
00:22:52,425 --> 00:22:53,811
We'll start with this scene.

433
00:22:54,427 --> 00:22:55,844
Good night, Bernie. See you tomorrow.

434
00:22:55,845 --> 00:22:57,137
- Good night, Bernie.
- Good night.

435
00:22:57,138 --> 00:23:00,026
- You need me for anything, Bernie?
- No.

436
00:23:00,767 --> 00:23:02,153
Want me to turn off the border?

437
00:23:02,268 --> 00:23:04,906
- Yeah. Good night.
- Good night.

438
00:23:07,065 --> 00:23:08,941
I'm sorry, Bernie, about the words.

439
00:23:08,942 --> 00:23:10,286
It's just that,

440
00:23:11,486 --> 00:23:13,487
well, I've had a lot
of other things on my mind.

441
00:23:13,488 --> 00:23:15,166
I know you have.

442
00:23:15,740 --> 00:23:17,282
Every time I give you a direction,

443
00:23:17,283 --> 00:23:19,420
I have the feeling you're
off in space somewhere.

444
00:23:20,119 --> 00:23:21,787
Frank, you can be great in this part,

445
00:23:21,788 --> 00:23:24,164
but it demands your
undivided concentration

446
00:23:24,165 --> 00:23:25,707
and every ounce of energy you've got.

447
00:23:25,708 --> 00:23:26,908
I know.

448
00:23:27,252 --> 00:23:29,430
I know,
I keep telling myself that, Bernie.

449
00:23:29,754 --> 00:23:32,600
And then after rehearsal,
I go home to study, and there's...

450
00:23:34,008 --> 00:23:36,468
Well, you've got headaches enough
of your own.

451
00:23:36,469 --> 00:23:38,106
- Good night.
- Frank?

452
00:23:39,138 --> 00:23:40,733
Having trouble at home?

453
00:23:41,266 --> 00:23:42,986
No, nothing like that.

454
00:23:45,186 --> 00:23:47,073
What's the matter?
Don't you believe me?

455
00:23:48,857 --> 00:23:50,535
Everyone has trouble at home.

456
00:23:51,901 --> 00:23:54,914
The only ones who deny it
are those that have too much of it.

457
00:23:56,114 --> 00:23:58,876
I denied it for five years
with the former Mrs. Dodd.

458
00:23:59,200 --> 00:24:01,295
Funny, I never had the impression
that you were married.

459
00:24:03,037 --> 00:24:04,549
Neither did my wife.

460
00:24:04,998 --> 00:24:06,342
That was my trouble.

461
00:24:08,001 --> 00:24:09,201
What's yours?

462
00:24:11,379 --> 00:24:14,172
It's nothing important. It'll work out.

463
00:24:14,173 --> 00:24:15,393
I'll see you in the morning.

464
00:24:15,550 --> 00:24:17,801
Does your wife
really want you to play this part?

465
00:24:17,802 --> 00:24:19,397
Yeah, she's all for it.

466
00:24:19,929 --> 00:24:21,149
I was just wondering.

467
00:24:22,015 --> 00:24:25,153
The day I met her, she seemed
a little difficult about terms.

468
00:24:26,019 --> 00:24:29,396
- Rather domineering, I thought.
- She wasn't always like that.

469
00:24:29,397 --> 00:24:30,825
I know, I know.

470
00:24:31,566 --> 00:24:35,360
They all start out as Juliets
and wind up as Lady Macbeths.

471
00:24:35,361 --> 00:24:39,500
When I first met her, she was
as fine a person as you've ever seen.

472
00:24:40,575 --> 00:24:42,462
She had background and breeding.

473
00:24:44,120 --> 00:24:47,133
She had a kind of a nobility about her

474
00:24:47,999 --> 00:24:50,511
that just made me feel proud
to be with her.

475
00:24:51,210 --> 00:24:53,765
Of course, I was a good deal older
than she was,

476
00:24:54,547 --> 00:24:56,476
but it didn't seem to make any difference,

477
00:24:56,716 --> 00:24:59,312
because she wasn't a flighty kid
or anything like that.

478
00:24:59,761 --> 00:25:02,273
She had a poise
and a dignity that was ageless.

479
00:25:04,974 --> 00:25:06,694
Those first few years, I...

480
00:25:07,310 --> 00:25:09,363
I just never knew a better life.

481
00:25:10,730 --> 00:25:14,243
A wife who was everything
I'd always been looking for

482
00:25:15,109 --> 00:25:18,331
and a son who was smart and healthy.

483
